<p>
    I included this chart because there were many more races in Pathfinder that I didn't feel were statistically siginifcant enough to show in the previous chart, but still said were interesting enough to beg their own chart. This chart produced possibly the most surprising 
    conclusion, the lack of play for the Vampire race. Vampires are a fantasy staple, having been in many cultures mythology for hundreds, if not thousands of years. They have been the target of many works of media and have otherwise stayed relevant for a fantasy race. Given 
    all of that, I would think that if Vampires were a playable option, players would gravitate towards it. They are popular, cool, and offer very interesting ways of playing the game. The two reasons why Vampires might not be played often that I can come up with is that
    they could have come near the end of the release of Pathfinder, or that Vampires tend to gravitate towards evil alignments. Evil alignments in games are hard to play around unless you are playing an evil campaign because the goals of an evil player character often go
    against what the good or even neutral characters want to do. No one wants to try and play two campaigns at once, so evil characters are typically relegated to evil campaigns.
</p>
